er after the game, as he has something to give her. Afterward, in the locker rooms, Bryce confronts Montgomery over his rape of Tyler in front of Charlie. When Montgomery proudly confesses, Bryce threatens to reveal his threatening of other students during Hannah's trial to the police. During halftime, Jessica and her sexual assault survivor club start a protest, where they take off their clothes and paint themselves with red hand prints. When one of the jocks from Hillcrest touches Jessica inappropriately, the Liberty High team attacks the Hillcrest team. Other students join the brawl.\n\n''Present'': The parents check the students' alibis for the night of Homecoming. Tyler considers telling the police about his assault and Bryce's knowledge of it to protect Clay, but Clay refuses, telling him to come out when he is ready, and that he may want to tell someone else in case he is arrested. Tyler tells Jessica, who apologizes for mistreating him, and afterwards, confronts Montgomery. Principal Bolan tells Jessica to apologize for Homecoming or lose her position as student body president. Clay reveals to Justin that he writes fanfiction, and researched how to kill someone, which makes him look more guilty. His parents try to get him to tell them everything, but he becomes more upset that they don't believe he isn't capable of murder. Clay asks Tony to help him disappear. Justin meets with Seth to make a deal.\n\n----\n''Suspect'': Clay Jensen because of the text messages found on his phone.\n |LineColor       = 3F556D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 38\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 12\n |Title           = And Then the Hurricane Hit\n |DirectedBy      = Kevin Dowling\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Thomas Higgins & Hayley Tyler & Trevor Marti Smith|t=Allen MacDonald & M.K. Malone & Helen Shang|tfirst=y}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|8|23}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n''Flashbacks'': Clay watches Ani and Bryce kiss. Later, Bryce attacks Zach over Chloe, dislocating his knee and ending his football career. Ani spills red paint on herself and hurries home to remove it. Zach finds Bryce at the pier and attacks him. He throws his phone in the river and leaves Bryce to die while he reconciles with Chloe.\n\n''Present'': Tyler convinces Clay to come to an assembly where Jessica apologizes for the protests. Tyler and Justin publicly reveal that they are sexual assault survivors. In private, Justin tells Jessica his childhood experience. Clay is arrested. Tyler reports his sexual assault to the police. Monty is arrested. Ani tells Jessica that she slept with Bryce. Zach surrenders to the police, believing he killed Bryce. Deputy Standall reveals that Bryce drowned. Zach is released, but charged for assault and battery.\n----\n''Suspect'': Ani Achola because of the red paint on her clothes.\n |LineColor       = 3F556D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 39\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 13\n |Title           = Let the Dead Bury the Dead\n |DirectedBy      = [[John T. Kretchmer]]\n |WrittenBy       = Brian Yorkey\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|8|23}}\n |ShortSummary    = ''Flashbacks'': Shortly following the Homecoming game, everyone's alibis are revealed: Tony was laundering money through the Mexican cartel for his deported family, Justin was dealing and going under the influence from drugs at the docks, and Monty is revealed to not have been at Charlie's house, but was sleeping with Winston. Bryce, having been abandoned at the pier, is met by both Alex and Jessica, who ignore Bryce's pleas for reformation, but hands Jessica a cassette tape. Alex helps him up, but when Bryce threatens retaliation against Zach, Alex becomes furious and pushes Bryce into the river, where he drowns. Jessica ends her relationship with Alex, after which they go home.\n\n''Present'': Ani tells the details of the circumstances leading to Bryce's murder to Deputy Standall, instead telling him that Monty was responsible for the murder, since Monty had threatened to kill Bryce earlier in the Homecoming game, and that he didn't have a strong alibi. Deputy Standall reveals that Monty was killed in his jail cell, to which Ani encourages Standall to close the case quickly by blaming the murder on a man already dead. Deputy Standall quickly deduces Alex was the killer, but doesn't mention anything, and burns all of Alex's clothes that he was wearing the night of Bryce's death. Clay and Mrs. Walker come to terms with each other, and Ani begins dating Clay. The group, who have agreed to cover up Alex's involvement as the killer, plays Bryce's tape, where he confesses to his rapes, but shows remorse for them and apologizes, although having come to terms that nobody will allow him to change. Tyler showcases his photography project at Monet's, as tribute for everyone who has helped him since his sexual assault. Meanwhile, Winston, angry over Monty's death, confronts Ani about lying to the police. Elsewhere, a fisherman finds the discarded bag of assault rifles that Clay, Tony and Tyler hid in the river during Spring Fling.\n----\n ''Suspect'': Montgomery de la Cruz because of the fight he had with Bryce in the change rooms.\n |LineColor       = 3F556D\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[Universal Studios]] purchased film rights to the novel on February 8, 2011, with [[Selena Gomez]] cast to play Hannah Baker.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schwartz |first=Terri |title=Selena Gomez To Star In '13 Reasons Why': Movie, adapted from Jay Asher's young adult novel, looks back at a girl's reasons for committing suicide. |work=MTV News |date=February 9, 2011 |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1657538/selena-gomez-13-reasons-why.jhtml |accessdate=April 11, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419040926/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1657538/selena-gomez-13-reasons-why.jhtml |archivedate=April 19, 2012}}</ref> On October 29, 2015, it was announced that [[Netflix]] would be making a television adaptation of the book with Gomez instead serving as an executive producer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Netflix Gives Selena Gomez's '13 Reasons Why' Straight-To-Series Order |url=http://deadline.com/2015/10/netflix-gives-selena-gomez-13-reasons-why-straight-to-series-order-1201597481/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=October 29, 2015 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030002121/http://deadline.com/2015/10/netflix-gives-selena-gomez-13-reasons-why-straight-to-series-order-1201597481/ |archivedate=October 30, 2015|date=October 29, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/selena-gomez-13-reasons-why-netflix-1201620194/ |title=Netflix Adapting '13 Reasons Why' Into Selena Gomez Series (Exclusive) |last=Wagmeister |first=Elizabeth |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=October 29, 2015 |accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref> [[Tom McCarthy (director)|Tom McCarthy]] was hired to direct the first two episodes.<ref name=mccarthy>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title=Spotlight's Tom McCarthy To Direct & Produce Selena Gomez's Netflix Series '13 Reasons Why' From Paramount TV |url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/spotlight-tom-mccarthy-direct-selena-gomez-13-reasons-why-netflix-1201708767/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=February 25, 2016 |accessdate=July 19, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711234328/http://deadline.com/2016/02/spotlight-tom-mccarthy-direct-selena-gomez-13-reasons-why-netflix-1201708767/ |archivedate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> The series is produced by [[Anonymous Content]] and [[Paramount Television]] with Gomez, McCarthy, Joy Gorman, [[Michael Sugar]], [[Steve Golin]], Mandy Teefey, and Kristel Laiblin serving as executive producers.<ref name=mccarthy/>\n\nOn May 7, 2017, it was announced that Netflix had renewed the series for a second season, which was released on May 18, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/13-reasons-why-renewed-season-2-netflix-2-1202411389/ |title='13 Reasons Why' Renewed for a Second Season at Netflix |date=May 7, 2017 |work=Variety |access-date=May 7, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507202901/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/13-reasons-why-renewed-season-2-netflix-2-1202411389/ |archivedate=May 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, 2018, Netflix renewed the series for a third season, which was released on August 23, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/13-reasons-why-renewed-season-3-netflix-1202404504/|title='13 Reasons Why' Renewed For Season 3 By Netflix|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=June 6, 2018|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=June 6, 2018}}</ref> It was dedicated to executive producer Steve Golin (founder and CEO of Anonymous Content), who died of [[Ewing's sarcoma]] on April 21, 2019, four months before the third season's release.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nOn August 1, 2019, it was announced that the series had been renewed for a fourth and final season.<ref name=\"S3PremiereDate&S4Renewal\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nIn June 2016, Dylan Minnette, Katherine Langford, Christian Navarro, Alisha Boe, Brandon Flynn, Justin Prentice, Miles Heizer, Ross Butler, Devin Druid and Brian d'Arcy James were cast as the main leads.<ref name=\"James\" /> In September, Amy Hargreaves, Kate Walsh and Derek Luke were cast.<ref name=\"Hargreaves\" /><ref name=\"WalshLuke\" /> Langford exited the show after the second season.\n\nIn September 2018, Timothy Granaderos and Brenda Strong were promoted to series regulars for season 3 after recurring in the previous seasons.<ref name=\"GranaderosStrong\" /> On September 5, 2019, [[Gary Sinise]] was cast as a series regular for the fourth season.<ref name=\"GarySinise\"/> On February 11, 2020, JanLuis Castellanos joined the cast as a series regular for the fourth season.<ref name=\"JanLuisC\"/><!--main cast only-->\n\nIn August 2017, Jake Weber, Meredith Monroe, R.J Brown, Anne Winters, Bryce Cass, Chelsea Alden, Allison Miller, Brandon Butler, Samantha Logan, Kelli O'Hara, and Ben Lawson were cast for season two.<ref name=\"S2CastDeadline\" /><ref name=\"S2CastVariety\" /><!--recurring cast only-->\n\n===Filming===\nFilming for the series took place in the [[Northern California]]n towns of [[Vallejo, California|Vallejo]], [[Benicia, California|Benicia]], [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]], [[Crockett, California|Crockett]] and [[Sebastopol, California|Sebastopol]] during the summer of 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mara |first1=Janis |title=Marin Netflix series shoot brings economic benefits |url=http://www.marinij.com/article/NO/20160623/NEWS/160629919 |accessdate=April 4, 2017 |work=Marin Independent Journal |date=June 23, 2016 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404220028/http://www.marinij.com/article/NO/20160623/NEWS/160629919 |archivedate=April 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/06/24/selena-gomez-produced-netflix-series-shooting-in-marin-brings-economic-benefits/ |title=Selena Gomez-produced Netflix series shooting in Marin brings economic benefits |last=Mara |first=Janis |date=June 24, 2016 |website=The Mercury News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211081745/http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/06/24/selena-gomez-produced-netflix-series-shooting-in-marin-brings-economic-benefits/ |archive-date=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref> The 13-episode first season and the special were released on Netflix on March 31, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title=Diana Son Joins Selena Gomez's Netflix Series '13 Reasons Why' As Showrunner |url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/diana-son-jselena-gomez-netflix-series-13-reasons-showrunner-1201709770/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=February 26, 2016 |accessdate=September 16, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917075908/http://deadline.com/2016/02/diana-son-jselena-gomez-netflix-series-13-reasons-showrunner-1201709770/ |archivedate=September 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/13-reasons-why-netflix-premiere-date-selena-gomez-jay-asher-1201893972/ |last=Petski |first=Denise |title='13 Reasons Why Gets Netflix Premiere Date |date=January 25, 2017 |access-date=April 1, 2017 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206062727/http://deadline.com/2017/01/13-reasons-why-netflix-premiere-date-selena-gomez-jay-asher-1201893972/ |archivedate=February 6, 2017}}</ref> [[Therapy dog]]s were present on set for the actors because of the intense and emotional content of the series.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keaney |first1=Quinn |title=How Netflix's 13 Reasons Why Is the Most Important YA Adaptation Yet |url=https://www.popsugar.co.uk/celebrity/13-Reasons-Why-Interview-Dylan-Minnette-Katherine-Langford-43403798 |work=PopSugar Celebrity UK |date=April 7, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411031906/https://www.popsugar.co.uk/celebrity/13-Reasons-Why-Interview-Dylan-Minnette-Katherine-Langford-43403798 |archivedate=April 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFilming for the second season began on June 12, 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/13-reasons-why-season-2-filming-starts/ |last=Fuller |first=Becky |title=13 Reasons Why Season 2 Begins Filming |date=June 12, 2017 |access-date=December 21, 2017 |website=Screen Rant}}</ref> but was briefly halted in October in response to the [[October 2017 Northern California wildfires|then-ongoing Northern California wildfires]] happening around the areas where the series was being filmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/13-reasons-why-production-shut-down-wildfires-northern-california-1202185999/|title='13 Reasons Why' Shuts Down Production Due To Devastating Northern California Wildfires|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=October 11, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=May 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Production on the second season wrapped in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/13-reasons-why/news/a845167/13-reasons-why-season-2-2018-netflix/ |title=13 Reasons Why season 2 has wrapped filming, ahead of a 2018 launch on Netflix |last=Roker |first=Sarah |work=[[Digital Spy]] |date=December 12, 2017 |accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref> The second season was released on May 18, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/13-reasons-why-season-2-premiere-date-netflix-1202791730/ |title='13 Reasons Why' Season 2 Premiere Date, Trailer Revealed |first=Todd |last=Spangler |work=Variety |date=April 30, 2018 |accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFilming for the third season began on August 12, 2018, but was halted due to [[Camp Fire (2018)|another wildfire]] until December 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/13-reasons-why-resumes-production-after-california-wildfire-shutdown/|title='13 Reasons Why' and Other Projects Resume Production After California Wildfire Shutdown|website=thewrap|access-date=March 28, 2019}}</ref> Filming was scheduled to be completed on February 6, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.girlfriend.com.au/everything-you-need-to-know-13-reasons-why-season-3|title=Everything you need to know about season 3 of '13 Reasons Why'|last=M|first=Bianca|date=November 12, 2018|work=[[Girlfriend (magazine)|Girlfriend]]|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\nInitially intended as a miniseries, the first season was released Netflix on March 31, 2017. It received positive reviews from critics and audiences, who praised its subject matter and acting, particularly the performances of Minnette and Langford. For her performance, Langford received a [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama]].<ref>{{Citation|title=2018 Golden Globe TV Nominations - Drama|url=https://www.eonline.com/ca/videos/266991/2018-golden-globe-tv-nominations-drama|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> However, its graphic depiction of issues such as suicide and rape (along with other mature content) prompted concerns from mental health professionals. In response, Netflix added a warning card and from March 2018 on, a video that plays at the start of each season warning viewers about its themes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/22/arts/television/netflix-warning-video-13-reasons-why.html |title=Netflix Adds a Warning Video to '13 Reasons Why' |last=Libbey |first=Peter |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 22, 2018 |accessdate=June 13, 2018 }}</ref> In July 2019, Netflix edited out the suicide scene in the first season's final episode.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/13-reasons-why-suicide-scene-hannah-baker-season-finale-death-katherine-langford-season-1-episode-13/|title=Netflix deletes graphic suicide scene from first season of \"13 Reasons Why\"|website=www.cbsnews.com|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite being initially produced and marketed as miniseries,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/amp/live-feed/big-little-lies-13-reasons-why-17-execs-why-they-keep-renewing-limited-series-1056663|title=17 Execs Explain Why They Keep Renewing Limited Series|first=Lesley|last=Goldberg|date=November 7, 2017|accessdate=February 1, 2020|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> Netflix renewed ''13 Reasons Why'' for a second season in May 2017 due to the success of the initial 13 episodes; filming of the second season began the next month and concluded that December. The second season was released on May 18, 2018, and received mixed to negative reviews from audiences. Coinciding with the release of the second season, Netflix released a video with the cast that cautioned viewers on some of the topics covered in the show and provided a support website with crisis numbers for people affected by depression, anxiety and other mental health issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmindustry.network/13-reasons-why-season-2-starts-mental-health-debate/32974|title=13 Reasons Why: Season 2 starts mental health debate|date=May 18, 2018|website=Film Industry Network|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> A third season was ordered in June 2018 and was released on August 23, 2019. In August 2019, the series had been renewed for a fourth and final season.<ref name=\"S3PremiereDate&S4Renewal\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/13-reasons-why-season-3-premiere-date-netflix-august-23-season-four-final-1202658562/|title='13 Reasons Why': Netflix Orders Fourth & Final Season Of Controversial Drama, Sets Season 3 Premiere Date|last=White|first=Peter|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=August 1, 2019|accessdate=August 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/13-reasons-why-season-3-premiere-date-netflix-renewed-final-season-4-1203287886/|title='13 Reasons Why' Renewed for Fourth and Final Season, Season 3 to Launch in August|last=Otterson|first=Joe|last2=Otterson|first2=Joe|date=August 1, 2019|website=Variety|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Critical and audience reaction to the series has been divided, with the program generating controversy between audiences and industry reviewers alongside acquiring a loyal following.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2017/05/05/13-reasons-why-suicide-mental-health-dangerous-column/101262330/|title='13 Reasons Why' spreads suicide like a disease: Column|website=USA Today|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2017/04/17/suicide-13-reasons-why-mental-illness-column/100562428/|title=How '13 Reasons Why' gets suicide wrong: Voices|website=USA Today|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/13-reasons-why-season-4-release-date-cast-story/1/|title=Here's What To Expect From 13 Reasons Why Season 4|date=August 25, 2019|website=ScreenRant|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Audience viewership===\nThe marketing analytics firm Jumpshot determined the first season was the second-most viewed Netflix season in the first 30 days after it premiered, garnering 48% of the viewers that the [[Daredevil (season 2)|second season]] of ''[[Daredevil (TV series)|Daredevil]]'' received, which was the most viewed season according to Jumpshot. The series also showed an 18% increase in week-over-week viewership from week one to week two. Jumpshot, which \"analyzes click-stream data from an online panel of more than 100 million consumers\", looked at the viewing behavior and activity of the company's U.S. members, factoring in the relative number of U.S. Netflix viewers who watched at least one episode of the season.<ref name=\"JumpshotViewers\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/netflix-marvel-the-defenders-binge-viewing-data-ratings-1202532453/ |title=Netflix's 'Marvel's The Defenders' Poised for Binge-Viewing Pop, Data Indicates |last=Spangler |first=Todd |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=August 18, 2017 |accessdate=August 19, 2017 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6sqg1uawF?url=http://variety.com/2017/digital/news/netflix-marvel-the-defenders-binge-viewing-data-ratings-1202532453/ |archivedate=August 20, 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#000814;\"|\n| 1\n| 79% (62 reviews)<ref name=\"RT\"/>\n| 76 (17 reviews)<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#8B96A9;\"|\n| 2\n| 25% (51 reviews)<ref name=\"RT2\"/>\n| 49 (16 reviews)<ref name=\"MC2\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#3F556D;\"|\n| 3\n| 12% (17 reviews)<ref name=\"RT3\"/>\n| 23 (4 reviews)<ref name=\"MC3\"/>\n|}\n\n====Season 1====\nThe first season has received positive reviews, with praise for the acting (particularly that of Minnette, Langford, and Walsh), directing, story, visuals, improvements upon its source material, and mature approach to dark and adult subject matter. The [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported an 79% approval rating with an average rating of 7.14/10, based on 62 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''13 Reasons Why'' complements its bestselling source material with a gripping look at adolescent grief whose narrative maturity belies its YA milieu.\"<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/13_reasons_why/s01 |title=13 Reasons Why: Season 1 (2017) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=February 19, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401133100/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/13_reasons_why/s01/ |archivedate=April 1, 2017}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned a score of 76 out of 100, based on 17 critics, indicating generally favorable reviews.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/13-reasons-why/season-1 |title=13 Reasons Why: Season 1 reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=August 20, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406055505/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/13-reasons-why |archivedate=April 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJesse Schedeen of [[IGN]] praised ''13 Reasons Why'', giving it a 9.2 out of 10, \"Amazing\", stating that the series is \"a very powerful and hard-hitting series\" and \"ranks among the best high school dramas of the 21st century\".<ref name=\"IGNresponse\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/04/05/13-reasons-why-season-1-review |title=13 Reasons Why: Season 1 Review |website=[[IGN]] |date=April 5, 2017 |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |accessdate=April 6, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406014923/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/04/05/13-reasons-why-season-1-review |archivedate=April 6, 2017}}</ref> Matthew Gilbert of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' gave a glowing review for the series, saying, \"The drama is sensitive, consistently engaging, and, most importantly, unblinking.\"<ref name=\"BGresponse\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/television/2017/03/28/reasons-why-brings-depth-teen-tragedy/WsqUdlmLuDnR8i6SmQi8cP/story.html |title=Yes, '13 Reasons Why' is for young adults. It's still very good. |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=March 29, 2017 |last=Gilbert |first=Matthew |accessdate=April 6, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407233119/https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/television/2017/03/28/reasons-why-brings-depth-teen-tragedy/WsqUdlmLuDnR8i6SmQi8cP/story.html |archivedate=April 7, 2017}}</ref> Maureen Ryan of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' asserts that the series \"is undoubtedly sincere, but it's also, in many important ways, creatively successful\" and called it \"simply essential viewing\".<ref name=\"Varietyresponse\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/reviews/13-reasons-why-review-netflix-selena-gomez-dylan-minnette-katherine-langford-1202013547/ |title=TV Review: '13 Reasons Why' on Netflix |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=March 21, 2017 |last=Ryan |first=Maureen |accessdate=April 6, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407144809/https://variety.com/2017/tv/reviews/13-reasons-why-review-netflix-selena-gomez-dylan-minnette-katherine-langford-1202013547/ |archivedate=April 7, 2017}}</ref> Leah Greenblatt of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the entire season a score of B+, calling the series \"a frank, authentically affecting portrait of what it feels like to be young, lost and too fragile for the world\".<ref name=\"EWresponse\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2017/03/22/13-reasons-why-ew-review/ |title=13 Reasons Why: EW review |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=March 22, 2017 |last=Greenblatt |first=Leah |accessdate=April 7, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408172810/https://ew.com/tv/2017/03/22/13-reasons-why-ew-review/ |archivedate=April 8, 2017}}</ref> Daniel Feinberg of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' also praised the series, calling it \"an honorably mature piece of young-adult adaptation\", and citing its performances, direction, relevance and maturity as some of the series' strongest points.<ref name=\"THRresponse\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/13-reasons-why-review-988413 |title='13 Reasons Why': TV review |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=March 27, 2017 |last=Fienberg |first=Daniel |accessdate=April 8, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408013912/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/13-reasons-why-review-988413 |archivedate=April 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe acting, particularly Katherine Langford as Hannah and Dylan Minnette as Clay, was frequently praised in reviews. Schedeen of [[IGN]] praised the cast, particularly Minnette and Langford, stating: \"Langford shines in the lead role{{nbsp}}... [and] embodies that optimism and that profound sadness [of Hannah's] as well. Minnette's Clay is, by design, a much more stoic and reserved character{{nbsp}}... and does a fine job in what's often a difficult role.\"<ref name=\"IGNresponse\" /> Gilbert of ''The Boston Globe'' praised the chemistry of Langford and Minnette, saying that \"watching these two young actors together is pure pleasure\", while Schedeen of IGN also agreed, saying that they are \"often at their best together, channeling just the right sort of warm but awkward chemistry you'd expect from two teens who can't quite admit to their feelings for one another\". Feinberg of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' also praises both actors: \"Langford's heartbreaking openness makes you root for a fate you know isn't possible. The actress' performance is full of dynamic range, setting it against Minnette's often more complicated task in differentiating between moods that mostly go from uncomfortable to gloomy to red-eyed, hygiene-starved despair.\"<ref name=\"THRresponse\" />\n\nRyan of ''Variety'' also gave praise to not only the two leads, but also the supporting cast of actors, particularly Kate Walsh's performance as Hannah's mother, which Ryan describes as \"career-best work\".<ref name=\"Varietyresponse\" /> Positive mentions from various critics, such as Ryan, Feinberg and Schedeen, were also given to the supporting cast of actors (most particularly Alisha Boe, Miles Heizer and Christian Navarro's respective performances of Jessica, Alex and Tony). Liz Shannon Miller of ''[[Indiewire]]'', who enjoyed the series and gave it a positive score of B+, gave praise to the racial, gender and complex diversity of its supporting cast of teens.<ref name=\"Varietyresponse\" /><ref name=\"IGNresponse\" /><ref name=\"THRresponse\" /><ref name=\"Indiewireresponse\" />\n\nAnother aspect frequently mentioned within reviews was the series's mature and emotional approach to its dark and adult subject matter. This was favorably reviewed by critics, such as Miller of ''Indiewire'', particularly her statement that \"the adult edges to this story ring with honesty and truth.\"<ref name=\"Indiewireresponse\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/03/13-reasons-why-review-netflix-suicide-1201799484/ |title='13 Reasons Why' review: Netflix brings a brutally adult edge to a tale of teen suicide |website=[[Indiewire]] |date=March 31, 2017 |last=Miller |first=Liz Shannon |accessdate=April 8, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410050418/https://www.indiewire.com/2017/03/13-reasons-why-review-netflix-suicide-1201799484/ |archivedate=April 10, 2017}}</ref> Miller, and Feinberg of ''The Hollywood Reporter'', also stated that the series can be difficult to watch at times,<ref name=\"THRresponse\" /> while Schedeen of IGN states that it is \"an often depressing and even uncomfortable show to watch{{nbsp}}... a pretty emotionally draining experience, particularly towards the end as the pieces really start to fall into place.\"<ref name=\"IGNresponse\" />\n\nCritics also praised several other aspects of the series. Feinberg highlighted the series' directors, saying: \"A Sundance-friendly gallery of directors including Tom McCarthy, Gregg Araki and Carl Franklin keeps the performances grounded and the extremes from feeling exploitative\",<ref name=\"Indiewireresponse\" /> while Gilbert of ''The Boston Globe'' praised the storytelling: \"The storytelling techniques are powerful{{nbsp}}... [as it] builds on the world established in the previous hour, as we continually encounter new facets of Hannah's life and new characters. The background on the show keeps getting deeper, richer.\"<ref name=\"BGresponse\" />\n\nConversely, the series has also received criticism over its portrayal of teen angst. Mike Hale of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote a critical review, writing, \"the show doesn't make [Hannah's] downward progress convincing. It too often feels artificial, like a very long public service announcement.\" He also criticized the plot device that has Clay listening to the tapes one by one instead of all in one sitting like the other teens did, which Hale felt was unbelievable: \"It makes no sense as anything but a plot device, and you'll find yourself, like Clay's antagonists, yelling at him to listen to the rest of tapes already.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hale |first1=Mike |title=Review: '13 Reasons Why' She Killed Herself, Drawn Out on Netflix |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/30/arts/television/netflix-13-reasons-why-tv-review.html |accessdate=April 10, 2017 |work=The New York Times |date=March 30, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410165508/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/30/arts/television/netflix-13-reasons-why-tv-review.html |archivedate=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[The Guardian]]'', Rebecca Nicholson praised some aspects of the series, including the performances from Minnette and Walsh, but was troubled by much of the plot, writing, \"a storyline that suggests the love of a sweet boy might have sorted all this out added to an uneasy feeling that stayed with me\". Nicholson was skeptical that the series would appeal to older viewers, unlike other series set in high school such as ''[[Freaks and Geeks]]'' and ''[[My So-Called Life]]'': \"It lacks the crossover wit of its forebears{{nbsp}}... It's too tied up in conveying the message that terrible behaviour can have horrible consequences to deal in any subtleties or shades of feeling. It's largely one-note \u2013 and that note is horrifying. 'It has to get better,' implores one student towards the end, but given its fairly open ending, an apparent season two setup, it does not seem as if there's much chance of that happening.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicholson |first1=Rebecca |title=13 Reasons Why review \u2013 sex, drugs and mixtapes in Netflix's high-school horror show |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/31/13-reasons-why-review-sex-drugs-and-mixtapes-in-netflix-high-school-horror-show |accessdate=April 12, 2017 |work=The Guardian |date=March 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411230644/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/31/13-reasons-why-review-sex-drugs-and-mixtapes-in-netflix-high-school-horror-show |archivedate=April 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Washington Post]]'' television critic [[Hank Stuever]] wrote a negative review, finding ''13 Reasons Why'' \"contrived\" and implausible: \"There are 13 episodes lasting 13 super-sullen hours \u2013 a passive-aggressive, implausibly meandering, poorly written and awkwardly acted effort that is mainly about miscommunication, delivering no more wisdom or insight about depression, bullying and suicide than one of those old ''[[After school special|ABC Afterschool Specials]]'' people now mock for being so corny.\" He also wrote that he found Hannah's suicide tapes \"a protracted example of the teenager who fantasizes how everyone will react when she's gone. The story{{nbsp}}... strikes me as remarkably, even dangerously, naive in its understanding of suicide, up to and including a gruesome, penultimate scene of Hannah opening her wrists in a bathtub.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stuever |first1=Hank |authorlink=Hank Stuever |title='Thirteen Reasons Why' shows how adults can really mess up teen angst |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/thirteen-reasons-why-shows-how-adults-can-really-mess-up-teen-angst/2017/03/30/c8db5f00-1346-11e7-9e4f-09aa75d3ec57_story.html |accessdate=April 12, 2017 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 30, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412075447/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/thirteen-reasons-why-shows-how-adults-can-really-mess-up-teen-angst/2017/03/30/c8db5f00-1346-11e7-9e4f-09aa75d3ec57_story.html |archivedate=April 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[David Wiegand]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the series a tepid review, saying that it was plagued by character inconsistencies, particularly Hannah. He praised Langford's \"stunning performance\" but noted, \"There are times when we simply don't believe the characters, when what they do or say isn't consistent with who we've been led to believe they are{{nbsp}}... At times, [Hannah] is self-possessed and indifferent at best to the behavior of the popular kids. At other times, though, relatively minor misperceived slights seem to send her into an emotional tailspin. No doubt, teenagers embody a constant whirl of conflicting emotions, but the script pushes the bounds of credibility here and there.\" He noted that overall, the series worked: \"The structure is gimmicky and the characters inconsistent, but there are still at least ''13 Reasons Why'' the series is worthy.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wiegand |first1=David |title='13 Reasons' why Netflix drama works despite gimmickry |url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/13-Reasons-why-Netflix-drama-works-despite-11034434.php |accessdate=April 19, 2017 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=March 29, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419192851/http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/13-Reasons-why-Netflix-drama-works-despite-11034434.php |archivedate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Season 2====\nThe second season received largely negative to mixed reviews from critics, with many praising the performances (particularly that of Boe, Luke, and Walsh) but criticism aimed at the poor execution of its topics; many declared it unnecessary.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rutledge |first1=Daniel |title=Teen suicide show 13 Reasons Why's second season suffers terrible reviews |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/entertainment/2018/05/teen-suicide-show-13-reasons-why-s-second-season-suffers-terrible-reviews.html |newspaper=Newshub |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |date=May 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Travis |title=Season 2 of Netflix's controversial hit '13 Reasons Why' is a huge misfire that critics are calling 'pointless' and 'boring' |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/13-reasons-why-season-2-critic-reviews-2018-5?IR=T |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |work=Business Insider |date=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Rotten Tomatoes reports an approval rating of 25% with an average rating of 5.31/10, based on 51 reviews. The site's critical consensus states, \"By deviating from its source material, ''13 Reasons Why'' can better explore its tenderly crafted characters; unfortunately, in the process, it loses track of what made the show so gripping in the first place.\"<ref name=\"RT2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/13_reasons_why/s02 |title=13 Reasons Why: Season 2 (2018) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> On Metacritic the season has an average score of 49 out of 100, based on 16 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref name=\"MC2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/13-reasons-why/season-2 |title=13 Reasons Why: Season 2 reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCatherine Pearson from [[DigitalSpy]] wrote a negative review, calling the season \"even more problematic\" than the first. She ends the review saying that, \"Unrelenting depression seems to shroud the season, briefly lifted only to collapse back down as the show's thirteenth episode, once again, delivers a deeply disturbing scene of suffering.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pearson |first1=Catherine |title=13 Reasons Why season 2 is even more problematic, with a troubling message for teens. |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/13-reasons-why/feature/a857634/13-reasons-why-season-2-episode-13-netflix-spoilers-review/ |accessdate=August 27, 2018 |work=DigitalSpy |date=May 25, 2018}}</ref> Jordan Davidson from ''The Mighty'' wrote that he \"felt sick\" after watching the final episode of the season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Davidson |first1=Jordan |title='13 Reasons Why' Season 2 Episode 13 Recap: 'Bye' |url=https://themighty.com/2018/05/13-reasons-why-season-2-episode-13-bye-recap-what-happens-to-tyler/ |website=The Mighty |accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA scene in which the character Tyler is attacked and sexually assaulted during the finale also caused controversy from fans and critics of the series, with some describing it as \"unnecessary\" and \"traumatizing\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/13-reasons-why-season-2-netflix-cancel-petition-school-shooting-rape-scene-a8363026.html|title=Netflix urged to cancel 13 Reasons Why after 'harmful' season 2 scenes|date=May 22, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> The series' showrunner has defended the scene, saying that it was included in an attempt to \"[tell] truthful stories about things that young people go through in as unflinching a way as we can\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/05/13-reasons-why-rape-season-2-finale-defends-1201967483/|title='13 Reasons Why' Creator Defends Graphic Season 2 Rape Scene, Questions If Backlash Is Due to Male-on-Male Assault|first=Zack|last=Sharf|date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Season 3====\nSeason 3 received overwhelmingly negative reviews by both critics and audiences, with criticism aimed at the lack of necessity, poor execution of its topics, including the rape of Tyler in the final episode of the previous season,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/article/13-reasons-why-season-3-recap-where-to-go-next/|title='13 Reasons Why' Season 3: Where do we go from here?|last=Khosla|first=Proma|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=September 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/13-reasons-why-season-3-review/|title=13 Reasons Why Season 3 Review: You Can't Get an A for Effort Anymore {{!}} TV Guide|date=August 27, 2019|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=September 3, 2019}}</ref> the new character of Ani,<ref name=\"heavy.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/08/13-reasons-why-season-3-narrator-ani/|title='13 Reasons Why' Season 3: Viewers Aren't Loving the New Narrator Ani|website=heavy.com|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref> the sympathetic redemption of Bryce<ref>[https://screenrant.com/13-reasons-why-season-3-mistake-bryce-walker/]</ref> and conclusion. However, some praised the technical aspects and the performances (particularly that of Prentice, Druid, and Strong).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/8/31/20840722/13-reasons-why-season-3-review|title=There are zero reasons why 13 Reasons Why season 3 should exist|last=Grady|first=Constance|date=August 31, 2019|website=Vox|access-date=September 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nReview aggregator Rotten Tomatoes reports an approval rating of 12%, with an average rating of 1.43/10, based on 17 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''13 Reasons Why'' attempts to break away from its first two seasons only to become a melodramatic mess of a murder mystery.\"<ref name=\"RT3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/13_reasons_why/s03 |title=13 Reasons Why: Season 3 (2019) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn Metacritic the season has an average score of 23 out of 100, based on 4 critics, indicating \"generally unfavourable reviews\".<ref name=\"MC3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/13-reasons-why/season-3 |title=13 Reasons Why: Season 3 reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\n[[File:1300_Reasons_WHY_NOT.jpg|thumb|[[Rowan University]]'s Counseling and Psychological Services office mocked the series with a campaign challenging students to come up with 1300 reasons not to kill themselves. The expressions of hope were hung in windows alongside mental health contact information.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snjtoday.com/story/36565018/rowan-students-faculty-share-1300-reasons-to-live |title=Rowan Students, Faculty Share '1,300 Reasons to Live' |last=Baratti |first=Nina |date=October 10, 2017 |website=SJN Today|access-date=}}</ref>]]\nSome medical professionals, school officials, and others who work with youth said that the series violated guidelines for depicting suicide in the media, and was resulting in an increase in suicidal and self-harming behavior. Netflix responded by adding strong advisory warnings prior to the first, twelfth, and thirteenth episodes.\n\nThe superintendent of [[Palm Beach County, Florida]] schools reportedly told parents that their schools had seen an increase in suicidal and self-harming behavior from students, and that some of those students \"have articulated associations of their at-risk behavior to the ''13 Reasons Why'' Netflix series\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Balingit |first1=Moriah |title=Educators and school psychologists raise alarms about '13 Reasons Why' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/educators-and-school-psychologists-raise-alarms-about-13-reasons-why/2017/05/01/bb534ec6-2c2b-11e7-a616-d7c8a68c1a66_story.html |accessdate=May 2, 2017 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Australian youth mental health service for 12\u201325 year-olds, [[headspace (organisation)|Headspace]], issued a warning in late April 2017 over the graphic content featured in the series, due to the increased number of calls to the service following the series' release in the country. [[Netflix]] however, demonstrably complied with the Australian viewer ratings system, by branding the series as \"MA15+\" when streamed via its own interface. They accompanied its presentation with additional warnings and viewer advice, and ensured that counselling referrals were included and not easily skipped at the conclusion of each episode. Each warning voice over is read by a different cast member at the end of the episode, with Katherine Langford reading in her native Australian accent in her voice-overs. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.communitynews.com.au/cockburn-gazette/news/13-reasons-headspace-issues-warning-new-netflix-show/ |title=13 Reasons Why: Headspace issues warning over new Netflix show |date=April 18, 2017 |publisher=[[Community Newspaper Group]] |accessdate=April 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419101534/http://www.communitynews.com.au/cockburn-gazette/news/13-reasons-headspace-issues-warning-new-netflix-show/ |archivedate=April 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/headspace-issues-warning-against-netflix-show-13-reasons-why/news-story/02014de19bd8daee573224c0c714eeae |title=Netflix series 13 Reasons Why under fire from mental health experts |work=news.com.au |accessdate=April 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418233845/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/headspace-issues-warning-against-netflix-show-13-reasons-why/news-story/02014de19bd8daee573224c0c714eeae |archivedate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.headspace.org.au/news/dangerous-content-in-13-reasons-why/ |title=headspace: dangerous content in 13 Reasons Why |work=headspace.org.au |accessdate=April 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419104903/https://www.headspace.org.au/news/dangerous-content-in-13-reasons-why/ |archivedate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the graphic nature of the series and New Zealand's high youth suicide rate, which was the highest among the 34{{efn|name=OECD note|The 2009\u20132012 data exclude Latvia, which became the 35th OECD member country on July 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oecd.org/document/58/0,3746,en_2649_201185_1889402_1_1_1_1,00.html |title=List of OECD Member countries \u2013 Ratification of the Convention on the OECD |website=Oecd.org |accessdate=April 28, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123031730/http://www.oecd.org/document/58/0%2C3746%2Cen_2649_201185_1889402_1_1_1_1%2C00.html |archivedate=November 23, 2015}}</ref>}} [[OECD]] countries during 2009 to 2012,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Social Report 2016 \u2013 Te p\u016brongo oranga tangata |url=http://socialreport.msd.govt.nz/health/suicide.html |publisher=Ministry of Social Development \u2013 New Zealand Government |accessdate=April 28, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406215234/http://socialreport.msd.govt.nz/health/suicide.html |archivedate=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mconnell |first1=Glenn |title=The highest rate of teen suicide in the developed world |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/85305366/the-highest-rate-of-teen-suicide-in-the-developed-world |website=Stuff.co.nz |accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref> the [[Office of Film and Literature Classification (New Zealand)|Office of Film & Literature Classification]] in the country created a new rating, \"RP18\", allowing individuals aged 18 and over to watch the series alone and those below having to watch it with supervision from a parent or guardian.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Zealand teens can only watch Netflix show 13 Reasons Why with their parents |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39732715/new-zealand-teens-can-only-watch-netflix-show-13-reasons-why-with-their-parents |website=BBC |accessdate=April 28, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427212208/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39732715/new-zealand-teens-can-only-watch-netflix-show-13-reasons-why-with-their-parents |archivedate=April 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=13 Reasons Why: Censors make new RP18 rating for controversial Netflix show |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/91956245/13-reasons-why-censors-make-new-rp18-rating-for-controversial-netflix-show |website=stuff.co.nz |accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote=We stayed very true to the book and that's initially what [author] [[Jay Asher]] created was a beautifully tragic, complicated yet suspenseful story and I think that's what we wanted to do{{nbsp}}... We wanted to do it justice and, yeah, [the backlash is] gonna come no matter what. It's not an easy subject to talk about, but I'm very fortunate with how it's doing.|source=\u2014Executive producer [[Selena Gomez]], in defense of the controversy surrounding the series<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/news/a44902/selena-gomez-responds-to-the-13-reasons-why-backlash |title=Selena Gomez Responds to the '13 Reasons Why' Backlash |access-date=April 29, 2017 |website=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |first=Kayleigh |last=Roberts |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430051736/http://www.elle.com/culture/news/a44902/selena-gomez-responds-to-the-13-reasons-why-backlash/ |archivedate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nIn April 2017, the [[National Association of School Psychologists]] (NASP) in the United States released a statement regarding the series, saying: \"Research shows that exposure to another person's suicide, or to graphic or sensationalized accounts of death, can be one of the many risk factors that youth struggling with mental health conditions cite as a reason they contemplate or attempt suicide.\"<ref name=\"CNN0425\">{{cite web |last1=Howard |first1=Jacqueline |title=Why teen mental health experts are focused on '13 Reasons Why' |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/04/25/health/13-reasons-why-teen-suicide-debate-explainer/ |website=CNN |accessdate=April 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426055938/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/04/25/health/13-reasons-why-teen-suicide-debate-explainer/ |archivedate=April 26, 2017}}</ref> NASP sent a letter to school mental health professionals across the country about the series, reportedly a first for NASP in response to a television series.<ref name=\"rollingstone5217\">{{cite news |last1=Blistein |first1=Jon |title=Netflix Adds More Advisory Warnings to '13 Reasons Why' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/netflix-adds-more-advisory-warnings-to-13-reasons-why-w480108 |accessdate=May 2, 2017 |work=Rolling Stone |date=May 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503062903/http://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/netflix-adds-more-advisory-warnings-to-13-reasons-why-w480108 |archivedate=May 3, 2017}}</ref> The following month, the United States [[Society of Clinical Child and Adolescent Psychology]] (SCCAP) released a statement also noting how strongly the series may serve as a trigger for self-injury among vulnerable youth. They lamented the depiction of mental health professionals as ineffective for youth who have experienced trauma and may have been considering suicide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Division 53 SCCAP Statement on 13 Reasons Why |url=https://clinicalchildpsychology.org/sccap-statement-13-reasons-why |website=clinicalchildpsychology.org |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref> The statement implored Netflix to add a tag following each episode with mental health resources, and a reminder that depression and suicidal thoughts can be effectively treated by a qualified mental health professional, such as a clinical child psychologist, using [[evidence-based practice]].\n\nSimilarly, [[clinical psychologists]] such as Daniel J. Reidenberg and Erika Martinez, as well as mental health advocate MollyKate Cline of ''Teen Vogue'' magazine, have expressed concerns regarding the risk of [[suicide contagion]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=MollyKate |first1=Cline |title=Why '13 Reasons Why' Can Be Triggering for People Coping With Mental Illness |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/04/25/health/13-reasons-why-teen-suicide-debate-explainer/ |website=Teen Vogue |accessdate=April 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426055938/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/04/25/health/13-reasons-why-teen-suicide-debate-explainer/ |archivedate=April 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Korin |title=13 Reasons Why Is Not the Force for Mental Health Awareness People Say It Is |url=http://www.self.com/story/13-reasons-why-suicide-and-mental-health |date=April 13, 2017 |website=Self |accessdate=April 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425205223/http://www.self.com/story/13-reasons-why-suicide-and-mental-health |archivedate=April 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thorbecke |first1=Catherine |title='13 Reasons Why' faces backlash from suicide prevention advocacy group |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/13-reasons-faces-backlash-suicide-prevention-advocacy-groups/story?id=46851551 |website=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=April 25, 2017 |date=April 18, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424112112/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/13-reasons-faces-backlash-suicide-prevention-advocacy-groups/story?id=46851551 |archivedate=April 24, 2017}}</ref> However, Eric Beeson, a counselor at The Family Institute at [[Northwestern University]] noted that \"it's unlikely that one show alone could trigger someone to attempt suicide.\"<ref name=\"CNN0425\"/> Mental health professionals have also criticized the series' depiction of suicide itself, much of which violates widely promulgated recommendations for reporting on actual suicides or not depicting them in fiction, in order to not encourage copycat suicides.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reportingonsuicide.org/recommendations/#important |title=Recommendations \u2013 Reporting on Suicide |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408043809/http://reportingonsuicide.org/recommendations/ |archivedate=April 8, 2017}}</ref> The season finale, which depicts Hannah's suicide in graphic detail, has been particularly criticized in this regard.<ref name=\"Slate piece\">{{cite news |last=Martinelli |first=Marissa |title=''13 Reasons Why'''s Controversial Depiction of Teen Suicide Has School Counselors Picking Up the Pieces |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2017/05/01/school_counselors_talk_netflix_s_controversial_teen_suicide_drama_13_reasons.html |newspaper=[[Slate (website)|Slate]] |date=May 1, 2017 |accessdate=May 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502022611/http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2017/05/01/school_counselors_talk_netflix_s_controversial_teen_suicide_drama_13_reasons.html |archivedate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> Nic Sheff, a writer for the series, has defended it as intended to dispel the myth that suicides \"quietly drift off\", and recalled how he himself was deterred from a suicide attempt by recalling a survivor's account of how painful and horrifying it was.<ref name=\"Sheff Vanity Fair essay\">{{cite news |last=Sheff |first=Nic |title=''13 Reasons Why'' Writer: Why We Didn't Shy Away from Hannah's Suicide |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/04/13-reasons-why-suicide-controversy-nic-sheff-writer |newspaper=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=April 13, 2017 |accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe NASP statement also criticized the series' suggestion that bullying alone led Hannah to take her life, noting that while it may be a contributing factor, suicide far more often results from the bullied person having a \"treatable mental illness and overwhelming or intolerable stressors\", along with a lack of adequate [[coping mechanism]]s. Alex Moen, a [[school counselor]] in Minneapolis, took issue with the series' entire plotline as \"essentially a fantasy of what someone who is considering suicide might have\u2014that once you commit suicide, you can still communicate with your loved ones, and people will suddenly realize everything that you were going through and the depth of your pain{{nbsp}}... That the cute, sensitive boy will fall in love with you and seek justice for you, and you'll be able to orchestrate it, and in so doing kind of still be able to live.\"<ref name=\"Slate piece\" /> Other counselors criticized the depiction of Hannah's attempt to reach out to Mr. Porter as dangerously misleading, since not only does he miss obvious signs of her suicidal ideations, but says he cannot report her sexual assault to the police without her identifying the assailant. School counselors are often portrayed as ineffective or clueless in popular culture, Moen says, but Porter's behavior in the series goes beyond that, to being unethical and possibly illegal. \"It's ridiculous! Counselors are not police. We don't have to launch an investigation. We bring whatever information we do have to the police\", she told ''[[Slate (website)|Slate]]''.<ref name=\"Slate piece\" />\n\nIn May 2017, the [[Canadian Mental Health Association]] (CMHA) along with the Centre for Suicide Prevention (CSP) released a statement with similar concerns to the ones raised by NASP. CMHA believed that the series may glamorize suicide, and that some content may lead to distress in viewers, particularly in younger viewers. Furthermore, the portrayal of Hannah's suicide does not follow the media guidelines as set out by the Canadian Association for Suicide Prevention (CASP) and the [[American Association of Suicidology]]. CMHA and CASP did praise the series for raising awareness about \"[[suicide|this preventable health concern]],\" adding that, \"Raising awareness needs to be done in a safe and responsible manner. A large and growing body of Canadian and international research has found clear links between increases in suicide rates and harmful media portrayals of suicide.\" Ways in which the portrayals of suicide may cause harm, according to CMHA and CASP, include the following: \"They may simplify suicide, such as, by suggesting that bullying alone is the cause; they may make suicide seem romantic, such as, by putting it in the context of a Hollywood plot line; they may portray suicide as a logical or viable option; they may display graphic representations of suicide which may be harmful to viewers, especially young ones; and/or they may advance the false notion that suicides are a way to teach others a lesson.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmha.ca/news/cmha-national-statement-responding-netflix-series-13-reasons/ |title=CMHA National Statement Responding to Netflix Series: 13 Reasons Why \u2013 Canadian Mental Health Association |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504044326/http://www.cmha.ca/news/cmha-national-statement-responding-netflix-series-13-reasons/ |archivedate=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nasponline.org/assets/documents/Resources%20and%20Publications/Resources/Crisis/13%20Reasons%20Why%20Guidance_FINAL.pdf National Association of School Psychologists. (2017). 13 Reasons Why Netflix series: Considerations for educators (handout). Bethesda, MD: Author. at nasponline.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606172516/http://www.nasponline.org/assets/Documents/Resources%20and%20Publications/Resources/Crisis/13%20Reasons%20Why%20Guidance_FINAL.pdf |date=June 6, 2017 }} Accessed May 8, 2017</ref> A 2019 study showed the overall suicide rate among 10- to 17-year-olds increased significantly in the month immediately following the release of the series.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bridge |first1=Jeffrey |title=Association Between the Release of Netflix's 13 Reasons Why and Suicide Rates in the United States: An Interrupted Times Series Analysis |journal=Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry |date=April 29, 2018 |doi=10.1016/j.jaac.2019.04.020 |pmid=31042568 |pmc=6817407 |url=https://www.jaacap.org/article/S0890-8567(19)30288-6/fulltext |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe release of ''13 Reasons Why'' corresponded with between 900,000 and 1.5 million more suicide-related searches in the United States, including a 26% increase in searches for \"how to commit suicide,\" an 18% increase for \"commit suicide,\" and a 9% increase for \"how to kill yourself.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ayers |first1=John W. |last2=Althouse |first2=Benjamin M. |last3=Leas |first3=Eric C. |last4=Dredze |first4=Mark |last5=Allem |first5=Jon-Patrick |title=Internet Searches for Suicide Following the Release of ''13 Reasons Why'' |journal=JAMA Internal Medicine |date=2017 |volume=177 |issue=10 |pages=1527\u20131529 |doi=10.1001/jamainternmed.2017.3333 |pmid=28759671 |pmc=5820689}}</ref> After an initial spike in calls to [[Crisis Text Line]] after the first episode, there was an overall reduction in crisis call volume for the remainder of the series.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=Laura K.|last2=Michael|first2=Kurt D.|last3=Runkle|first3=Jennifer|last4=Sugg|first4=Margaret M.|date=2019|title=Crisis Text Line use following the release of Netflix series 13 Reasons Why Season 1: Time-series analysis of help-seeking behavior in youth|journal=Preventive Medicine Reports|volume=14|pages=100825|doi=10.1016/j.pmedr.2019.100825|pmid=30828539|issn=2211-3355|pmc=6384324}}</ref> Although the link between searching for suicide information and suicide risk is unclear,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mok |first1=K |last2=Jorm |first2=AF |last3=Pirkis |first3=J |title=Suicide-related Internet use: A review. |journal=The Australian and New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry |date=August 2015 |volume=49 |issue=8 |pages=697\u2013705 |doi=10.1177/0004867415569797 |pmid=25698810|hdl=11343/58519 }}</ref> increases in self-harm admissions to one children's hospital were observed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cooper|first=Michael Townsend|last2=Bard|first2=David|last3=Wallace|first3=Rebecca|last4=Gillaspy|first4=Stephen|last5=Deleon|first5=Stephanie|date=2018|title=Suicide Attempt Admissions From a Single Children's Hospital Before and After the Introduction of Netflix Series 13 Reasons Why|journal=Journal of Adolescent Health|language=en|volume=63|issue=6|pages=688\u2013693|doi=10.1016/j.jadohealth.2018.08.028|pmid=30454731}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Till |first=Benedikt |last2=Vesely |first2=Christine |last3=Mairhofer |first3=Dunja |last4=Braun |first4=Marlies |last5=Niederkrotenthaler |first5=Thomas |date=2019 |title=Reports of Adolescent Psychiatric Outpatients on the Impact of the TV Series ''13 Reasons Why'': A Qualitative Study |journal=Journal of Adolescent Health |volume=64 |issue=3 |pages=414\u2013415 |doi=10.1016/j.jadohealth.2018.11.021|pmid=30819333 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-49001246|title=Netflix removes 13 Reasons Why suicide scene|date=July 16, 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/netflix-alters-graphic-13-reasons-why-suicide-scene-controversy-1224489|title=Netflix Alters Graphic '13 Reasons Why' Suicide Scene After Controversy|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/netflix-edits-13-reasons-why-suicide-scene-1202646773/|title=Netflix Edits '13 Reasons Why' Suicide Scene Following Complaints|last=Bennett|first=Anita|last2=Bennett|first2=Anita|date=July 16, 2019|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:23%;\"| Award\n! style=\"width:28%;\"| Category\n! style=\"width:32%;\"| Nominee(s)\n! style=\"width:9%;\"| Result\n! style=\"width:3%;\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2017\n| Gold Derby Awards\n| Breakthrough Performer of the Year\n| [[Katherine Langford]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.goldderby.com/article/2017/2017-gold-derby-tv-awards-winners-big-little-lies-news-357924086/ |title=2017 Gold Derby TV Awards winners: 'Big Little Lies' and 'SNL' sweep, while 'Stranger Things' takes Best Drama |last=Montgomery |first=Marcus James Dixon,Daniel |date=September 7, 2017 |work=GoldDerby|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"13\" | 2018\n| [[75th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama]]\n| Katherine Langford\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/awards/2018-golden-globe-winners-list-1202653737/ |title=Golden Globes Winners: Complete List |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 7, 2018 |accessdate=January 8, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108050125/https://variety.com/2018/film/awards/2018-golden-globe-winners-list-1202653737/ |archivedate=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.goldenglobes.com/tv-show/13-reasons-why Golden Globes]</ref>\n|-\n| [[Guild of Music Supervisors Awards]]\n| Best Music Supervision in a Television Drama\n| Season Kent\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/music/news/guild-of-music-supervisors-awards-nominations-1202661480/ |title=Imagen Foundation Announces Nominees for the 33rd Annual Imagen Awards | publisher= [[Imagen Awards|The Imagen Foundation]] |date=June 28, 2018 |accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Imagen Awards]]\n| Best Actor \u2013 Television\n| [[Christian Navarro]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imagen.org/2018/06/28/imagen-foundation-announces-nominees-for-the-33rd-annual-imagen-awards/ |title=NAACP Image Awards: 'Marshall,' 'Get Out,' 'Girls Trip' Dominate Film Nominations |author=THR Staff |date=November 20, 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2018 MTV Movie & TV Awards|MTV Movie & TV Awards]]\n| [[MTV Movie & TV Award for Best Show|Best Show]]\n| ''13 Reasons Why''\n| {{nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3079939/2018-mtv-movie-tv-award-winners/|title=2018 MTV Movie & TV Award Winners|work=[[MTV]]|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie & TV Award for Best Performance in a Show|Best Performance in a Show]]\n| Katherine Langford\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| [[49th NAACP Image Awards|NAACP Image Awards]]\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Directing in a Drama Series|Outstanding Directing in a Drama Series]]\n| [[Carl Franklin]] for \"Tape 5, Side B\"\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2018-naacp-image-award-nominations-complete-list-1057758 |title=NAACP Image Awards: 'Marshall,' 'Get Out,' 'Girls Trip' Dominate Film Nominations |author=THR Staff |date=November 20, 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[44th People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Awards]]\n| The Bingeworthy Show of 2018\n| ''13 Reasons Why''\n| {{Nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://eonline.com/shows/peoples_choice_awards/news/963752/2018-people-s-choice-awards-complete-list-of-nominations |title=2018 People's Choice Awards: Complete List of Nominations |work=[[E!]] |date=September 5, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |first=Johnni |last=Macke}}</ref>\n|-\n| The Drama Show of 2018\n| ''13 Reasons Why''\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| The Drama TV Star of 2018\n| Katherine Langford\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| The Show of 2018\n| ''13 Reasons Why''\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[22nd Satellite Awards|Satellite Awards]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress in a Drama / Genre Series]]\n| Katherine Langford\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/dunkirk-the-shape-of-water-lead-satellite-award-nominations/ |title='Dunkirk,' 'The Shape of Water' Lead Satellite Award Nominations |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=November 28, 2017 |accessdate=November 29, 2017 |first=Steve |last=Pond}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Drama Series]]\n| ''13 Reasons Why''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Television Academy Honors]]\n| Television with a Conscience\n| ''13 Reasons Why''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/andi-mack-13-reasons-why-among-recipients-of-11th-annual-television-academy-honors-1202383130/ |title='Andi Mack', '13 Reasons Why' Among Recipients Of 11th Annual Television Academy Honors |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=May 4, 2018 |accessdate=May 23, 2018 |first=Bruce|last=Haring}}</ref><ref>[https://www.emmys.com/awards/honors/eleventh/honoree1 Starting the Uncomfortable Conversation|Television Academy]</ref>\n|}\n\n==''Beyond the Reasons''==\nWith the release of the first season of the series, Netflix also released ''13 Reasons Why: Beyond the Reasons'' , an [[aftershow]] [[Television documentary|documentary television film]].<ref>[https://www.emmys.com/awards/honors/eleventh/honoree1 Starting the Uncomfortable Conversation|Television Academy]</ref> The 29-minute documentary featured cast and crew of the series, and mental health professionals discussing their experiences working on the four series and dealing with different issues, including bullying, depression and sexual assault. Two more ''Beyond the Reasons'' specials were released with the second and third seasons respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://decider.com/2018/05/30/13-reasons-why-beyond-the-reasons-season-2/ |title='13 Reasons Why' Viewers Need to Watch 'Beyond the Reasons' |last=Cobb |first=Kayla |website=[[Decider.com]] |date=May 30, 2018 |accessdate=June 14, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614175543/https://decider.com/2018/05/30/13-reasons-why-beyond-the-reasons-season-2/ |archivedate=June 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.netflix.com/title/80996791 |title=13 Reasons Why: Beyond the Reasons |publisher=[[Netflix]] |accessdate=June 14, 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180614180107/https://www.netflix.com/nl-en/title/80996791 |archivedate=June 14, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/video/4217709/13-reasons-why-season-2-beyond-the-reasons-trailer |title='13 Reasons Why' Season 2 'Beyond the Reasons' Trailer |publisher=[[Global News]] |date=May 18, 2018 |accessdate=June 14, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614175733/https://globalnews.ca/video/4217709/13-reasons-why-season-2-beyond-the-reasons-trailer |archivedate=June 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nA compilation soundtrack has been released for every season, as well as score albums featuring the show's original score by [[Eskmo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popsugar.com/node/43373162|title=Lose Yourself in 13 Reasons Why's Brilliant, Haunting Soundtrack|last=Keaney|first=Quinn|date=June 5, 2017|website=POPSUGAR Entertainment|language=en-US|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/04/13-reasons-why-soundtrack-netflix-1201803378/|title='13 Reasons Why' Soundtrack: Listen to This Haunting Playlist From Netflix's Heartbreaking Series|last=Nguyen|first=Hanh|last2=Nguyen|first2=Hanh|date=April 7, 2017|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popsugar.com/node/46534270|title=The Soundtrack For 13 Reasons Why Season 3 Features New Songs From Some of Your Faves|last=Prahl|first=Amanda|date=August 23, 2019|website=POPSUGAR Entertainment|language=en-US|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/05/13-reasons-why-soundtrack-season-2-songs-playlist-netflix-1201967950/|title='13 Reasons Why' Soundtrack: Listen to Season 2's Moody and Memorable Playlist|last=Nguyen|first=Hanh|last2=Nguyen|first2=Hanh|date=May 24, 2018|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n===Season 1===\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = 13 Reasons Why (A Netflix Original Series Soundtrack)\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = Various artists\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = {{start date|2017|03|30}}\n| studio       = \n| recorded     = \n| genre        = \n| length       = 52:21\n| label        = [[Interscope Records]]\n| producer     = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = 13 Reasons Why (A Netflix Original Series Soundtrack)\n | type        = soundtrack\n | single1     = [[Bored (Billie Eilish song)|Bored]]\n | single1date = March 30, 2017\n | single2     = [[The Killing Moon]]\n | s